\subsubsection{The PML in Three Dimensions}\label{PML_3d} 
The $PML$ for three dimensions closly follows the two-dimensional version. The only difference is that we have to deal with three directions instead of two\cite{Sullivan_simp_pml}. For instance, (\ref{pml_2d_1a}) becomes
\begin{eqnarray}\label{pml_3d_1}
j\omega \left(1+\frac{\sigma_x(x)}{j\omega\varepsilon_0}\right)\left(1+\frac{\sigma_y(y)}{j\omega\varepsilon_0}\right)\left(1+\frac{\sigma_z(z)}{j\omega\varepsilon_0}\right)^{-1}D_z&=&c_0\cdot\left(\frac{\partial H_y}{\partial x}-\frac{\partial H_x}{\partial y}\right)
\end{eqnarray}
and implementing it will closely follow the two-dimensional development. Start by rewriting (\ref{pml_3d_1}) as
\begin{eqnarray}\label{pml_3d_2}
j\omega \left(1+\frac{\sigma_x(x)}{j\omega\varepsilon_0}\right)\left(1+\frac{\sigma_y(y)}{j\omega\varepsilon_0}\right)D_z&=&c_0\left(1+\frac{\sigma_z(z)}{j\omega\varepsilon_0}\right)\cdot\left(\frac{\partial H_y}{\partial x}-\frac{\partial H_x}{\partial y}\right)\nonumber\\
&=&c_0\cdot curl_-h+c_0\cdot\frac{\sigma_z(z)}{\varepsilon_0}\frac{1}{j\omega}curl_-h
\end{eqnarray}
Define
\begin{eqnarray}\label{pml_3d_3}
I_{D_z}=\frac{1}{j\omega}curl_-h
\end{eqnarray}
which is an integration when it goes to the time domain, so (\ref{pml_3d_2}) becomes
\begin{eqnarray}\label{pml_3d_4}
j\omega \left(1+\frac{\sigma_x(x)}{j\omega\varepsilon_0}\right)\left(1+\frac{\sigma_y(y)}{j\omega\varepsilon_0}\right)D_z=c_0\cdot \left (curl_-h+\frac{\sigma_z(z)}{\varepsilon_0}I_{D_z}\right)
\end{eqnarray}
The implantation of this into FDTD parallel that of the two-dimensional PML, except the right side contains the integration term $I_{D_z}$. Therefore, following the same math we used in for two dimensional case, we get
\begin{subequations}\label{pml_3d_5}
\begin{eqnarray}
curl_-h&=&H_y^n(i+1/2,j,k+1/2)-H_y^n(i-1/2,j,k+1/2)\nonumber\\
&-&H_x^n(i,j+1/2,k+1/2)+H_x^n(i,j-1/2,k+1/2)\label{pml_3d_5a}\\
I_{D_z}^n(i,j,k+1/2)&=&I_{D_z}^{n-1}(i,j,k+1/2)+curl_-h\label{pml_3d_5b}\\
D_z^{n+1/2}(i,j,k+1/2)&=&gi3(i)gi3(j)D_z^{n+1/2}(i,j,k+1/2)\nonumber\\
&+&gi2(i)gj2(j) 0.5\left(curl_-h+gk1(k)I_{D_z}^n(i,j,k+1/2)\right)~~~~\label{pml_3d_5c}
\end{eqnarray}
\end{subequations}
In calculating the f and g parameters, it is not necessary to actually vary conductivities. Instead, we calculate an auxiliary parameter,
\begin{eqnarray}\label{pml_3d_6}\\
xn=\frac{\sigma\bigtriangleup t}{2\varepsilon_0}
\end{eqnarray}
that increases as it goes into the PML. The f and g parameters are then calculated:
\begin{eqnarray}\label{pml_3d_7}\\
xn(i)=0.333\times\left(\frac{i}{length_{-}pml}\right)^3~~~~~~i=1,2,3,.......,length_{-}pml
\end{eqnarray}
\begin{subequations}\label{pml_3d_8}
\begin{eqnarray}
fi1(i)&=&xn(i)\label{pml_3d_8a}\\
gi2(i)&=&\frac{1}{1+xn(i)}\label{pml_3d_8b}\\
gi3(i)&=&\frac{1-xn(i)}{1+xn(i)}\label{pml_3d_8c}
\end{eqnarray}
\end{subequations}
The quantity in parenthesis in (\ref{pml_3d_7}) ranges between 0 and 1. The factor \lq\lq 0.333\rq\rq was found empirically to be the largest number that remained stable \cite{Sullivan_unsplit_3d_pml}. Similarly, the cubic factor in (\ref{pml_3d_7}) was found empirically to be the most effective variation-fi2 and fi3 are different only because they are computed at the half intervals, i+1/2. The parameters vary in the following manner:
\begin{subequations}\label{pml_3d_9}
\begin{eqnarray}
fi1(i),gi1(i),fj1(j),gj1(j),fk1(k)~\&~gk1(k)~~~&&~~~\mathrm{from~0~to~0.333} \label{pml_3d_9a}\\
fi2(i),gi2(i),fj2(j),gj2(j),fk2(k)~\&~gk2(k)~~~&&~~~\mathrm{from~0~to~0.75} \label{pml_3d_9b}\\
fi3(i),gi3(i),fj3(j),gj3(j),fk3(k)~\&~gk3(k)~~~&&~~~\mathrm{from~0~to~0.5} \label{pml_3d_9c}
\end{eqnarray}
\end{subequations}

Though the main problem space, fi1(i), gi1(i), fj1(j), gj1(j), fk1(k) \& gk1(k) are zero and fi2(i), gi2(i), fj2(j), gj2(j), fk2(k), gk2(k), fi3(i), gi3(i), fj3(j), gj3(j), fk3(k) \& gk3(k) are one. Therefore, there is a \lq\lq seamless\rq\rq transition from the main part of the program to the PML(Fig.~\ref{Fig:2d_cross_section_of_pml}), but it suffers from main drawback: the integral parameter $I_{D_z}$ is an additional three-dimensional array that is dimensioned through the problem space, but used only two edges. The three-dimensional implementation will have a total six such arrays, which clearly is a waste of computer resources. For this reason, $I_{D_z}$ will be broken up into two smaller three-dimensional arrays, one define at the low value of i,j or k and one define at the high values of i, j or k as in \cite{Sullivan_book_00}. 







































